The argument of Cicero is summed up by Victorinus, p. 246, who quotes it as an example of a quinquepertita argumentatio, thus, ‘talis in Miloniana oratione syllogismus est, si, inquit, doceo causas fuisse Clodio, ut occideret Milonem, probo insidiatorem. Hanc propositionem approbavit, etsi boni

. . . saepepmuo. Deinde ipsam speciem assumit per confirmationem: habuitautem causas Clodius. Hanc rursus assump tionem multis rationibus approbat: pos- tremo concludit: qnare si habuit causas Clodius, ut occideret Milonem, constat in· sidiatoremsuisse! As this conclusio does not appear in our text, recent editors mark a lacuna. Peyron, arguing from the number of lines contained in a fol. of P, had calculated that the missing folio —containing etsi nullo § 3² . . . fuerit occidi 5 34-would require to fill it four or five more lines, than are given in our MSS, using this argument to justify his insertion above. The lacuna here is supposed to be of this length: ‘desunt quinque scre versus’ Nohl. The words of Victorinus however, who is quoting very loosely, need not mean that the con- clusion is expressed. On internal evidence Ishouldlookontbeargumentascomplete. Cicero, through want of facts has ventured upon a striking exmmatio in the shape of an attack upon Sex. Clodius. After this display of stage passion he quits the subject, before the hearer recollects that after all nothing has been proved. I should be curious to see a rammi, which would not create a bathos [see p. liii]. The argument from the number of lines contained in P is unreliable, since we do not know how much is lost in the new sentence before fuerit occidi.
